indelsClassification: classification of short insertions and deletions for mutational signature analysis

Ferran Nadeu (nadeu@clinic.ub.es)

11/10/2018

The indelsClassification R function performs the classification of small insertions and deletions (indels) in 84 classes following the criteria described in The Repertoire of Mutational Signatures in Human Cancer (Alexandrov et al., bioRxiv 2018). An extra indel class has been added to account for “complex insertions/deletions” (see the PCAWG7_indel_classification_2017_12_08_modified_by_FNadeu.xlsx document for details).

This functions takes as input a 4-column matrix with CHROMOSOME, POSITION, REF, ALT and returns a list with two objects:

  • Matrix with the 5’ and 3’ context of the indels and their classification (note that the nucleotide at POSITION is included both in the 5’ and 3’ context sequences)
  • Graphical representation of the classification

indelsClassification - Toy example

Libraries

library(GenomicRanges)
library(BSgenome)
library(BSgenome.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg19)
library(Rsamtools)

Source indelsClassification function

source("indelsClassification.R")

Load data

INDELS <- read.table("indelsClassification_toyExample.tsv", sep = "\t", header = T, stringsAsFactors = F)
# head(INDELS) 
kable(head(INDELS), align = "l") # for fancy rmarkdown tables
Chrom Pos Ref Alt
1 20496058 TAAAG T
1 23665181 GT G
1 30315110 GA G
1 50723455 T TA
1 62416864 GA G
1 63669074 CT C

Run indelsClassification function

out <- indelsClassification(mat = INDELS)

Check the classification matrix

# head(out[[1]]) 
kable(head(out[[1]]), align = "l") # for fancy rmarkdown tables
CHR POSITION REF ALT context5p context3p indelClass indelSubClass indelRepeats
chr1 20496058 TAAAG T GTAAT TAAAGAAAATCCCAGTGCCGTAAGCAAAGAG deletion with microhomology 4 3
chr1 23665181 GT G TG GTTACATTCAATA 1bp deletion T:A 2
chr1 30315110 GA G GG GAAAAAAAGGCAA 1bp deletion T:A 6+
chr1 50723455 T TA GT TAAAAAAACAGTG 1bp insertion T:A 5+
chr1 62416864 GA G GG GAAAAAAAAAGTT 1bp deletion T:A 6+
chr1 63669074 CT C TC CTTTTTTTTTGGT 1bp deletion T:A 6+

Plot indel classification

out[[2]]

# grid::grid.newpage() # run this in your R script to open a new page for the next plot

Plot the indel classification re-using the previous annotation

It is useful for large datasets so you only need to annotate the indels once, and then you can re-use this annotation when plotting again the same indels or just a subset of them.

INDELS <- cbind(INDELS, out[[1]][, 5:9])
indelsClassification(mat = INDELS[1:200, ], classColumn = "indelClass", subClassColumn = "indelSubClass", repeatsColumns = "indelRepeats")[[2]]

# grid::grid.newpage() # run this in your R script to open a new page for the next plot

Customize title, subtitle and y-axis

indelsClassification(mat = INDELS, classColumn = "indelClass", subClassColumn = "indelSubClass", repeatsColumns = "indelRepeats", title = "My title", subtitle = T, yScale = "count")[[2]]
